When a variable is declared as `static`, it means that it is shared by all instances of the class. In other words, there is only one copy of the variable, and it is not reinitialized every time a new instance of the class is created.

Here's an example in Java:
```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int count = 0; // static variable

    public MyClass() {
        count++; // increment the static variable
    }
}
```
